# VFX Master Library - Jurassic Survival Game
# Transpersonal Game Studio - VFX Agent #17
# CYCLE_ID: PROD_JURASSIC_001

## ARCHITECTURE OVERVIEW

This document defines the complete VFX architecture for our Jurassic survival game, following the principle that "VFX serves narrative and mechanics — never itself."

### PERFORMANCE TARGETS
- 60fps PC / 30fps Console maintained at all times
- 3-tier LOD system for all effects
- Maximum 50 simultaneous particle systems in view
- Memory budget: 128MB for all VFX assets

### CORE VFX CATEGORIES

#### 1. ENVIRONMENTAL EFFECTS
**Purpose:** Create living, breathing world atmosphere
**Examples:** Rain, fog, dust particles, ambient insects
**Performance:** Tier 1 priority - always visible

#### 2. CREATURE INTERACTION EFFECTS
**Purpose:** Enhance dinosaur behaviors and player interactions
**Examples:** Footstep dust, breathing steam, territorial markings
**Performance:** Tier 2 priority - distance-based LOD

#### 3. SURVIVAL MECHANICS EFFECTS
**Purpose:** Visual feedback for gameplay systems
**Examples:** Fire, smoke, blood, tool impacts
**Performance:** Tier 1 priority - gameplay critical

#### 4. TEMPORAL/MAGICAL EFFECTS
**Purpose:** Support the time-travel narrative element
**Examples:** Gem energy, temporal distortion, discovery moments
**Performance:** Tier 3 priority - story moments only

#### 5. DESTRUCTION & IMPACT EFFECTS
**Purpose:** Visceral feedback for dangerous encounters
**Examples:** Wood splinters, rock debris, ground impacts
**Performance:** Tier 2 priority - combat situations

### TECHNICAL SPECIFICATIONS

#### Niagara System Standards
- All effects use Niagara (no legacy Cascade)
- GPU simulation preferred for performance
- Modular design - reusable emitters
- Data-driven parameters for easy iteration

#### LOD Chain Implementation
**LOD 0 (0-20m):** Full quality, all features enabled
**LOD 1 (20-50m):** Reduced particle count, simplified shaders
**LOD 2 (50m+):** Billboard imposters, minimal particles

#### Material Standards
- Maximum 3 texture samples per VFX material
- Use vertex colors for variation when possible
- Translucent materials use Alpha Composite blend mode
- All materials support distance-based opacity fade

### NAMING CONVENTIONS

#### Systems
NS_[Category]_[Effect]_[Variation]
Example: NS_Env_Rain_Heavy

#### Emitters
NE_[Category]_[Effect]_[Component]
Example: NE_Env_Rain_Droplets

#### Materials
M_VFX_[Category]_[Effect]
Example: M_VFX_Env_RainDroplet

#### Textures
T_VFX_[Type]_[Effect]_[Channel]
Example: T_VFX_Noise_Rain_RGB

### INTEGRATION REQUIREMENTS

#### Audio Integration
- All impact effects trigger audio events
- Particle count drives audio intensity
- Distance-based audio occlusion support

#### Lighting Integration
- Fire effects cast dynamic light
- Lightning effects use temporary light sources
- Particle systems respect global lighting conditions

#### Physics Integration
- Debris effects use Chaos physics
- Particle collisions with world geometry
- Wind effects respond to weather system

This master library will be expanded as production progresses, but establishes the foundation for all VFX work.